Hi, i have this repo: https://bitbucket.org/marcos_vel_zquez_barocio/goappmx

It displays the message: "This repository&#x27;s size is over 1 GB" ;

even when i used the garbage collector and try the tutorials on https://confluence.atlassian.com/pages/viewpage.action;jsessionid=EED548093E6735F62ED685D61F2239F4.node2?pageId=273877699;

Can you help me to check why do i still get this error?

Thanks.

When using links to header anchors in markdown local file links do not work. External file links work, provided they do not contain spaces. this is from within a branch, not master.

{code}
#!markdown
[link](#markdown-header-header1)

[link1](filename-no-spaces.md#markdown-header-header1)

[link2](filename with spaces.md#markdown-header-header1)

[reference another file][another-file.md#markdown-header-header1)

{code}

Link1 produces a link to the parent directory with &#x27;#markdown-header-header1&#x27;

link2 bounces around commits or branches, either way 404&#x27;s are produced

link3 replaces all file spaces with %2520 over %20 (url encoded %20) and again produces 404&#x27;s

reference another file link works as expected, including going to the header1 anchor.

Apologies if this is not the correct place to report this.

EDIT:

Further study has found the above is not acurate.

The problem is, for some files, they attempt to link as if they are in the master branch, when no file of that name exists in the master branch

File1 in branch 1 with link

{code}
#!markdown

[link](#markdown-header-local-link)
{code}

Will try to resolve to a file that doesn&#x27;t exist in the master branch and as such will link to {{folder/#markdown-header-local-link}} in the master branch

For the same reason (it seems) if the filename is added before the anchor link, it attempts to go to the master branch folder {{folder/filename#markdown-header-local-link}} and as that file doesn&#x27;t exist in master it produces a 404 page. This holds true when linking to these files from other files within &#x27;branch 1&#x27; as well

[The Snippets API documentation|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BITBUCKET/snippets%2Bendpoint#snippetsEndpoint-GETallsnippets] suggests that role is not required when requesting all snippets.

However, calling the endpoint without the role parameter is returning an error:

{code}
#!python

 Error:
{ message: &#x27;Mandatory query parameter "role" missing (specify "owner", "contributor", or "member")&#x27; }
{code}

Steps to reproduce:

# Change / add a file to your repo which contains a {{+}} character (common in obj-c projects). Example: {{MyProject/NSString+Extras.h}}
# Observe it says- "Oops! You&#x27;ve got a lot of code in this diff and it couldn&#x27;t load with the page. Click here to give it another chance."
# Click on &#x27;Click here to give it another chance&#x27;

_Expected result_: can see diff

_Actual result_:  cannot diff the file and Bitbucket reports "Now that is a lot of code! There&#x27;s simply too much in this diff for us to render it all." even if file is tiny.

Thanks for fixing [issue#=6315|https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issue/6315/relative-urls-in-readmemd-files-only-work] and its duplicates (e.g., [issue#=6589|https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issue/6589/markdown-relative-link-to-image-and-other]. However, as noted [here|https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issue/6589/markdown-relative-link-to-image-and-other#comment-17834020], those issues address relative-linking from one file (e.g., a {{README}}) to another (e.g., an image) within a given project&#x27;s repository. That&#x27;s useful, but IMHO It Would Be Better to also to support relative links from a wikipage to a file in the project&#x27;s repository. E.g., suppose

# One has a project with name={{project_name}} rooted @ {{.../project_name/}}
# The project&#x27;s owner creates a readme visible as project overview at the canonical location={{.../project_name/README}}
# The project&#x27;s owner creates a wiki at the canonical location={{.../project_name/wiki/}}
# The project&#x27;s owner creates a folder/subdir @ {{.../project_name/images/}} and commits files to the project repo in that folder/subdir.

Currently (i.e., since the fix to [issue#=6315|https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issue/6315/relative-urls-in-readmemd-files-only-work] and its duplicates), the following relative-link syntaxes (doubtless et al) work (as demonstrated by my [project={{rst_link_test}}|https://bitbucket.org/tlroche/rst_link_test]:

# from {{.../project_name/README}} to {{.../project_name/images/image_file}} with the following syntax:

## {{/images/image_file}}
## {{./images/image_file}}
## {{images/image_file}}
# from {{.../project_name/wiki/Home}} to an {{image_file}} in the project&#x27;s Downloads with the (sole) syntax {{../downloads/Jen_Sorensen_PandP-poster-ForWeb.png}} as demonstrated [here|https://bitbucket.org/tlroche/rst_link_test/wiki/Home#rst-header-an-image]

I realize that [you currently intend to keep wiki repositories separate from their project&#x27;s repo|https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issue/7874/incorporate-wiki-in-source-repository-bb]. That being said, the [currently-supported behavior|https://bitbucket.org/tlroche/rst_link_test/wiki/Home#rst-header-id28] seems to demonstrate that there is no technical impediment to a wikipage relative-linking to a file in its project&#x27;s repo.
